          <span><strong>Language:</strong> Urdu → Arabic/English</span>
        </div>
        <div class="snapshot-item">
          <i class="fas fa-clock"></i>
          <span><strong>Translation:</strong> 2-4 hours</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>What Is a Nikah Nama?</h2>
      <p>The Nikah Nama (نکاح نامہ) is Pakistan's official Islamic marriage contract. It's a legal document registered with the local Union Council and serves as proof of marriage for all legal purposes. The document follows a standardized format established by Pakistani family law.</p>
      <p>Key characteristics:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Language:</strong> Urdu (with Arabic Islamic phrases)</li>
        <li><strong>Format:</strong> Pre-printed form with handwritten entries</li>
        <li><strong>Columns:</strong> 20+ numbered sections covering all marriage terms</li>
        <li><strong>Authority:</strong> Registered by a Nikah Registrar (مسجل نکاح) with the Union Council</li>
        <li><strong>Legal status:</strong> Primary proof of marriage under the Muslim Family Laws Ordinance, 1961</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>The 20+ Columns Explained</h2>
      <p>Understanding the Nikah Nama structure helps you verify your translation is complete. Here are the key columns:</p>

      <div class="column-grid">
        <div class="col-group">
          <h3>Identity & Registration</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Column 1-3:</strong> Registration number, date, and district</li>
            <li><strong>Column 4-5:</strong> Groom's name, father's name, CNIC, age</li>
            <li><strong>Column 6-7:</strong> Bride's name, father's name, CNIC, age</li>
            <li><strong>Column 8:</strong> Whether bride was previously married</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-group">
          <h3>Marriage Terms</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Column 9-10:</strong> Haq Mehr (dower) — amount and payment terms (muajjal/muwajjal)</li>
            <li><strong>Column 11-12:</strong> Witnesses — two male witnesses with CNIC numbers</li>
            <li><strong>Column 13:</strong> Wali (guardian) details and consent</li>
            <li><strong>Column 14:</strong> Vakil (representative) if bride/groom absent</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-group">
          <h3>Conditions & Signatures</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Column 15-17:</strong> Special conditions (talaq delegation, maintenance terms)</li>
            <li><strong>Column 18:</strong> Declaration of consent (ijab and qubool)</li>
            <li><strong>Column 19:</strong> Signatures of bride, groom, witnesses, wali</li>
            <li><strong>Column 20:</strong> Nikah Registrar seal and signature</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-box">
        <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>Every Column Must Be Translated</strong>
          <p>UAE entities reject Nikah Nama translations that skip columns — even columns marked with a dash or "N/A." The translation must be complete. Our translators work through every column systematically, noting empty or illegible entries explicitly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Attestation Chain (Pakistan → UAE)</h2>
      <p>Pakistan is NOT a Hague Convention member. The full attestation chain is required:</p>

      <div class="process-steps">
        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">1</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Union Council Verification</h3>
            <p>The Nikah Nama must be verified by the Union Council where the marriage was registered. This confirms the document is genuine and on record. Some Union Councils issue a duplicate if the original is lost.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">2</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Deputy Commissioner / District Office</h3>
            <p>The document goes to the Deputy Commissioner or District Administration for attestation. This is a state-level authentication confirming the Union Council's authority.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">3</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Pakistan MOFA</h3>
            <p>The Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Islamabad attests the document. This confirms the district-level authentication. Processing: 3-5 business days at the Islamabad office.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">4</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>UAE Embassy in Islamabad</h3>
            <p>The UAE Embassy (or Consulate in Karachi) attests the Pakistan MOFA stamp. Processing: 3-7 business days.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">5</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>UAE MOFA + MOJ Translation</h3>
            <p>Once in the UAE, <a href="/services/attestation/mofa/">MOFA attestation</a> completes the chain. We then produce the MOJ Arabic translation. Total UAE-side: 1-2 days for attestation + same-day translation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Nikah Nama vs NADRA Certificate</h2>
      <div class="comparison-table-wrapper">
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Aspect</th>
              <th>Nikah Nama</th>
              <th>NADRA Marriage Certificate</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Format</strong></td>
              <td>Pre-printed form, handwritten entries</td>
              <td>Computerized, typed text</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Language</strong></td>
              <td>Urdu (with Arabic phrases)</td>
              <td>English and Urdu</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Content</strong></td>
              <td>Full 20+ columns, all marriage terms</td>
              <td>Summary extract of key details</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Translation Difficulty</strong></td>
              <td>High (handwriting, terminology)</td>
              <td>Low (typed, standardized)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>UAE Acceptance</strong></td>
              <td>Accepted everywhere</td>
              <td>Accepted by most entities</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Our Recommendation</strong></td>
              <td colspan="2">Have both attested. Submit the NADRA certificate first (faster processing). Keep the Nikah Nama as backup if specifically requested.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Common Translation Issues</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Illegible handwriting:</strong> Nikah Registrars vary in penmanship. Some entries may be partially illegible. Professional translators note illegible entries rather than guessing.</li>
        <li><strong>Islamic legal terminology:</strong> Terms like mahr muajjal (prompt dower), mahr muwajjal (deferred dower), talaq-e-tafweez (delegated divorce), and iddat require precise Arabic/English equivalents.</li>
        <li><strong>Name transliteration:</strong> Urdu names transliterate differently to English than to Arabic. The English transliteration must match the passport exactly. "Muhammad" vs "Mohammed" vs "Mohammad" matters.</li>
        <li><strong>Witness CNIC numbers:</strong> Some Nikah Namas have incomplete or illegible CNIC numbers for witnesses. The translation must reflect what's on the document.</li>
        <li><strong>Special conditions (Column 15-17):</strong> These columns may contain specific marriage conditions or be left blank. Both scenarios need accurate translation — blank columns noted as "no conditions specified."</li>
        <li><strong>Haq Mehr amount:</strong> The dower amount in Pakistani Rupees must be accurately translated. If expressed in gold (tola), the measurement must be preserved.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Other Pakistani Documents for UAE</h2>
      <p>Beyond the Nikah Nama, Pakistani nationals commonly need these documents attested and translated:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">Birth certificates</a> — from NADRA or Union Council</li>
        <li><a href="/personal/academic/degree/">Degree certificates</a> — HEC attested + full chain + <a href="/resources/mohesr-equivalency/">MOHESR equivalency</a></li>
        <li><a href="/personal/immigration/pcc/">Police clearance (PCC)</a> — from Pakistan Police + attestation</li>
        <li><a href="/personal/vital-records/divorce/">Divorce decree</a> — from Family Court + attestation</li>
        <li><a href="/personal/immigration/bank/">Bank statements</a> — MOJ translation if needed</li>
        <li><a href="/personal/immigration/license/">Driving license</a> — for UAE license exchange</li>
      </ul>
      <p>All Pakistani documents follow the same attestation chain (no Hague apostille). See our <a href="/services/attestation/pakistan/">Pakistan attestation guide</a> for the complete process.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <RelatedServices
        pageKey="pakistaniGuide"
        title="Related Services"
        showFamily={true}
        showCrossSilo={true}
        maxItems={6}
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        {faqs.map((faq, index) => (
          <details class="faq-item" open={index === 0}>
            <summary class="faq-question">{faq.question}</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer"><p>{faq.answer}</p></div>
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container cta-section">
      <h2>Nikah Nama Translation</h2>
      <p>Send your Nikah Nama via WhatsApp. We'll review the document quality, confirm attestation status, and provide a quote. If any columns are illegible, we'll let you know before you pay.</p>
      <p>For full attestation chain details, see our <a href="/resources/pakistani-marriage-certificate-uae/" style="color: var(--accent-coral);">Pakistani Marriage Certificate Attestation Guide</a> covering the complete embassy chain and NADRA certificates.</p>
      <a href="https://wa.me/971508620217?text=I%20need%20Nikah%20Nama%20translation%20for%20UAE" class="btn btn-primary">
        <i class="fab fa-whatsapp"></i> Send Nikah Nama for Review
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

